SIMPLE: upon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Upon
<hw>Up*on"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos><ety>[AS.
<ets>uppan</ets>, <ets>uppon</ets>; <ets>upp</ets> up + <ets>on</ets>,
<ets>an</ets>, on. See <er>Up</er>, and <er>On</er>.]</ety> <def>On; --
used in all the senses of that word, with which it is
interchangeable.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Upon</xex> an hill of flowers.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our host <qex>upon</qex> his stirrups stood anon.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt take of the blood that is <qex>upon</qex> the
altar.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxix. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Philistines be <qex>upon</qex> thee, Samson.</q>
<rj><qau>Judg. xvi. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As I did stand my watch <qex>upon</qex> the hill.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He made a great difference between people that did rebel
<qex>upon</qex> wantonness, and them that did rebel <qex>upon</qex>
want.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This advantage we lost <qex>upon</qex> the invention of
firearms.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Upon</qex> the whole, it will be necessary to avoid that
perpetual repetition of the same epithets which we find in Homer.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had abandoned the frontiers, retiring <qex>upon</qex>
Glasgow.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Philip swore <qex>upon</qex> the Evangelists to abstain from
aggression in my absence.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Upon</xex> conveys a more distinct notion that
<xex>on</xex> carries with it of something that literally or
metaphorically bears or supports. It is less employed than it used to
be, <xex>on</xex> having for the most part taken its place. Some
expressions formed with it belong only to old style; as, <xex>upon</xex>
pity they were taken away; that is, in consequence of pity:
<xex>upon</xex> the rate of thirty thousand; that is, amounting to the
rate: to die <xex>upon</xex> the hand; that is, by means of the hand: he
had a garment <xex>upon</xex>; that is, upon himself: the time is coming
fast <xex>upon</xex>; that is, upon the present time. By the omission of
its object, <xex>upon</xex> acquires an adverbial sense, as in the last
two examples.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To assure upon</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to
promise; to undertake.</cd> -- <col><b>To come upon</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Come</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To take upon</b></col>, <cd>to
assume.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Up-over</ent>⟦br⟧
